What are the points on the other side? Is it not evident here that the King of Spain has confiscated this property? Is not this the property of subjects, with reference to which the earlier opinion of Baldus was set down? But the Spanish law brought about the confiscation, the Spanish law which is the same as the King. But the Ambassador asks for the confiscation, and he is the King here to all intents and purposes. It does not count for the Dutch enemy, does it, that they are within their rights in taking from the Spanish and in making the stolen property their own?
